Founder‚Äôs insight

Being a founder is chaotic ‚Äî endless decisions, problems, and ideas pulling you in different directions. Staying focused is hard, but I‚Äôve learned that CLARITY is the key.

Here‚Äôs what helps me:

-

Exercise: Running and strength training clear my mind and energize me. A strong body fuels a sharp mind.

-

Reflection: I regularly step back to prioritize what matters most‚Äîwhether it‚Äôs scaling 10Web or being present for my kids.

-

Simple systems: I build systems for work and life, like clear OKRs or point systems for motivating my kids, so I can focus on what really matters.

-

Listening to myself: I pay attention to how I feel ‚Äîwhether it‚Äôs about energy levels, focus, or stress‚Äîand adjust quickly when something‚Äôs off.

The chaos will never disappear, but with clarity, you can navigate it with purpose and control.

column8: Three Traits That Differentiate Great Senior Data Engineers
column10:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/three-traits-that-differentiate-great

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here üëã
Before diving into today‚Äôs newsletter, I want to take a moment to thank this issue‚Äôs sponsor: Hex [ https://substack.com/redirect/92f81202-2af4-4f24-aa77-d0ffdd02781e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Hex brings the magic of AI to data analysis workflows, whether you‚Äôre using code or no-code. Hex helps organizations work together with data and avoid jumping between different data tools for querying, data science, visualization, and spreadsheets. Over 1600 organizations use Hex to do everything from deep analysis to self-serve.
Now let‚Äôs jump into the article!
Early in my career I had a conversation with a friend who was working as a director leading both software and data teams. 
One of the points they brought up was the fact that they often found that some of their senior level analysts and data scientists would provide them massive chart dumps when they ran any form of analysis.
Somewhere deep in a word document or python notebook layered with charts and explanations might be a conclusion. 
I had actually not considered this point before having this conversation. 
Now it‚Äôs been years since that chat and since then I‚Äôve had nearly a hundred conversations with data leaders, and several skills and traits kept standing out in terms of what differentiates engineers and analysts. Here are three of them.
Getting Buy-In And Influencing Decisions
I don‚Äôt recall who told me this idea before, but someone once described that at every level(junior, mid, senior, etc), there are levels inside it. This breaks down into more ‚Äújunior‚Äù and ‚Äúsenior‚Äù at that specific level. 
Once you start going from a more ‚Äújunior senior‚Äù to a ‚Äúsenior senior‚Äù many data leaders I‚Äôve spoken with are looking to see if their ICs can start to get buy-in for their projects. 
At this level many senior engineers [ https://substack.com/redirect/41396ef5-413e-41bd-9fa3-82aed3a04dfd?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and analysts [ https://substack.com/redirect/b126393c-a558-4e58-a9a3-a8db0a85d28d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] are likely starting to feel antsy. Like they should be promoted to staff. And although every company has a different definition of what staff means, having the ability to get buy-in came up several times as a differentiator.
This is hard because it involves a combination of skills and traits.
You need to be able to communicate an idea
You need to have built some credibility in the organization
You need to be able to understand the needs of other teams
Each of these aspects require time. But, you don‚Äôt have to start with some massive project.
How to Build Buy-In as a Senior IC
Start Small ‚Äì Pick a recurring pain point, propose a lightweight fix, and see it through. If you‚Äôve never got buy-in for a small idea, you won‚Äôt be used to what push back you‚Äôll get nor will you have the credibility [ https://substack.com/redirect/2c65982b-263c-4a7c-8b44-a65add8a2bf6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to lean on. 
Draft a short one-pager - This should outline the problem, impact, and a lightweight solution. We often think other people are in our heads and get what we mean when we say it. Writing things down often highlight where teams might not be aligned or where issues will arise. So do it and figure out how to resolve said issues.
Socialize Early ‚Äì Float ideas in 1:1s before you ‚Äúpitch.‚Äù I had plenty of ideas get shot down because I never asked individuals around the key stakeholder what they might think of the pitch. Nor did I bring anyone else in on the idea so they could feel they had helped shape the idea.
Map Stakeholders ‚Äì Know who‚Äôs affected and what each group values. There will always be push back, especially when you start asking for larger requests. Prepare for it based on the various stakeholders [ https://substack.com/redirect/28296909-ade0-47c4-a036-d8ac2b4a6ef6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Deliver Consistently ‚Äì Reliability is credibility. At the end of the day, if you‚Äôre not delivering, all the pre-work won‚Äôt matter.
Show Impact ‚Äì Translate technical work into business outcomes, time saved, ROI. Don‚Äôt just talk about the technical improvements as this likely won‚Äôt land.
Prioritization And Scope Discipline
I put prioritization and scope discipline together as they have plenty of cross over. Both generally require the ability to say no as well as the ability to create a clear path of what can and cannot be done.
Working as a leader on a data team [ https://substack.com/redirect/ffe15c2e-afc5-46c3-9b3d-44de299ab0ac?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], whether an IC lead like at the Staff level or manager means you‚Äôll have endless requests to automate financial reporting, provide marketing numbers, build external reporting for partners while trying to keep your current pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/5b511aaa-9033-4175-8260-67412f2b0c73?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] running(unless you work for a more specialized data team).
Not to mention cross functional teams constantly increasing the scope of the current projects you are working on. 
What if we added another filter?
Could we remove that metric?
Can we add a new metric?
What if we calculated this metric using this other method?
For both of these skills I find that you need to be able to get the business on board by:
Helping Them See The Full Path - Whether you‚Äôre building a data product or trying to manage a half dozen projects. Putting together either a visual or one-pager that shows how you will tackle the next few steps helps get everyone on board.
Define the ‚Äúgood enough‚Äù version early - Before the project starts, write down what V1 looks like, the minimal version that delivers value. This helps stop scope creep later. Trust me, if you don‚Äôt it‚Äôll drag on far past the delivery date.
Create visible tradeoffs. When someone requests an addition, show what gets delayed or dropped if it‚Äôs added. For example: ‚ÄúWe can add the new feature to the marketing dashboard now, but it means the marketing attribution model slips by three weeks.‚Äù
SeattleDataGuy‚Äôs Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Deliver A Concise Analysis Or Recommendation
As referenced in the beginning of this article, a common area many data leaders want to see growth in is how information is conveyed. In particular with data analysis, and recommendations.
It‚Äôs tempting to discuss the how and every number you crunched first before the why. 
In practice, this often looks like:
Walking through every query or model tweak before getting to the conclusion
Sharing every chart instead of the two that matter
Writing a ten-page document when a one-slide summary would have done the job
Delivering an analysis that is concise doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôve got to cut out information from the analysis as a whole. It does mean you need to highlight the main point first. There are probably lots of interesting data points you picked up as you were digging into the data.
Those can be interesting talking points but they can also distract from what you are trying to drive home. Your stakeholders might stop you and start asking about those interesting facts instead of staying on topic.
Now you‚Äôre stuck doing a deeper dive into a totally new angle that keeps you from actually taking action [ https://substack.com/redirect/f7406275-963a-4f64-bb85-d11b9af4fdf7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
So keep it simple, for example:
‚ÄúOur conversion rate dropped 15% last quarter, primarily due to a pricing change in our mid-tier plan.‚Äù
You would likely also add what this would mean towards your companies larger goals and if you had any good ideas, suggest them.
But too much more than that and you‚Äôll be digging into some other angle instead of trying to fix the drop in conversion.
I actually recently asked Tessa Xie [ https://substack.com/redirect/6726e15f-71c9-49a6-95e1-1417e739ebae?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] to put together a video on how to deliver an impactful analysis. If you‚Äôre interested in viewing it, let me know and I‚Äôll send it your way!
Some Other Points I‚Äôve Written On In The Past
In the past I‚Äôve written several articles covering other skills and traits that data leaders have mentioned differentiate their senior and staff-level team members. You can read them below!
Ask Better Questions To Your Cross Functional Partners [ https://substack.com/redirect/ca6d0d10-0dc2-447a-ba46-3f5f23880b16?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Take Ownership [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6bda058-1778-4a1d-b797-5f3a5720407a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Learn To Take Calculated Risks [ https://substack.com/redirect/78741acf-a058-4628-b16a-f10323afd6d1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Communicate Trade-Offs [ https://substack.com/redirect/cda1eb8c-ef01-44ce-ab35-9c6fd019a661?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Anticipate What The Business Needs [ https://substack.com/redirect/b09e85b6-6293-4c14-b644-bdaa5e081031?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Communicate The Business Where They Are [ https://substack.com/redirect/cda1eb8c-ef01-44ce-ab35-9c6fd019a661?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Final Thoughts
Over the past decade it‚Äôs interesting to see how so many things have changed. Airflow was open-sourced when I first started my career, Hadoop was at it‚Äôs peak and Snowflake and Databricks [ https://substack.com/redirect/3b894e33-8c06-4721-8380-51e5d4e9ac43?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] were really just getting started.
So many things have changed on the technology side. However, the conversations I am having with both business and data leaders about the traits they want to see from their senior and staff-level team members haven‚Äôt changed much.
They want people to take ownership, and to understand the business better.
Truthfully, doing all of this is hard while you‚Äôre also trying to keep up with everything that is changing on the technology side. 
But small things you do every day can help.
Asking yourself:
Will the person receiving this analysis get the point fast enough?
Could I put together a visual to help simplify this concept?
Will taking on this next ask keep us from delivering what we currently have? And if so, how can I better communicate why that is and what can actually be done?
Can help you improve in small ways that compound over your career.
As always, thanks as always for reading.
Upcoming Data Events I‚Äôll Be At
Queries, Cocktails & Community - Small Data SF Happy Hour [ https://substack.com/redirect/7470feee-87cc-4638-8fd0-a0fcf9cf0e3d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Small Data SF [ https://substack.com/redirect/52c9ad1c-915d-4d46-949e-2a68c4f51678?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
Rebuilding Uber‚Äôs Apache Pinot‚Ñ¢ Query Architecture
Built on Apache Pinot‚Ñ¢, the real-time analytics platform at Uber powers hundreds of critical use cases, from user-facing analytics and experiences to massive internal platforms like log search, tracing, and more. Until 2024, nearly all of the hundreds of millions of daily Pinot queries were served from Neutrino, an internal fork of Presto¬Æ optimized for low latency and high QPS. While our Neutrino-based query architecture has served us well over the years, we‚Äôve also faced significant challenges in building a coherent query system over this layered architecture.
Transitioning away from Neutrino seemed extraordinarily challenging a few years ago, since Neutrino could run complex OLAP queries with multiple sub-queries and window functions at high QPS and low latency with minimal reliability risks. While Pinot‚Äôs MSE (Multi-Stage Engine [ https://substack.com/redirect/7b96c1bb-e098-4308-805e-3ebc9fdb4656?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]) was promising, it was originally aimed at adding full Distributed SQL support, with a focus on completeness. A new MSE query could easily involve large scans or huge joins on arbitrarily large tables, which could impact a tenant‚Äôs reliability.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/50358f29-87c3-4974-ac3e-6a8d05d0a7a3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Understanding the ‚ÄúT‚Äù in ETL: A Back-to-Basics Guide to Data Transformations
Over the past year, I‚Äôve been writing about several back-to-the-basics topics, like extracting data via APIs and SFTP, and building solid data models. But I realized I hadn‚Äôt yet touched on the ‚ÄúT‚Äù in ELT/ETL: transformations.
And that‚Äôs where data and analytics engineers often spend a lot of their time, whether it‚Äôs standardizing inputs or layering in business logic.
So in this article, I‚Äôll break down what transformations are, why they matter, and walk through a few examples.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/95920500-5f9b-4713-bd09-b37bc1ab482a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
End Of Day 199
Thanks for checking out our community. We put out 4-5 Newsletters a month discussing data, tech, and start-ups.
If you enjoyed it, consider liking, sharing and helping this newsletter grow.

column9:
View this post on the web at https://blog.dataengineer.io/p/the-2025-ai-enabled-data-engineering

AI is making manually writing complex data pipelines a thing of the past! If AI is writing the pipelines, what tasks are left for data engineers to work on? 
Conceptual knowledge is becoming king in 2025 and onward! 
DataEngineer.io Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
In this article we will cover:
How AI will be impact data engineering
What skills and responsibilities are more/less vulnerable to AI
How tools like Cursor [ https://substack.com/redirect/2ca5419b-853f-4825-8f35-f5410d1e1995?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and Windsurf [ https://substack.com/redirect/14db93ff-9024-4d83-95cc-9dde5f760a4e?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] make development much faster
What design patterns and best practices should you know as a data engineer to supercharge your career with AI
How AI will impact data engineering
This is the area where data engineers are worried. Will AI take all the jobs? How will things look in the future? 
You can think of data engineering responsibilities on a few axes:
Technical and Tactical (hard skills that have a day-to-day focus)
Writing Spark and SQL code - medium risk of disruption
Tools like Cursor and Windsurf make the codegen here much faster. You still need to test and look over the code though so it‚Äôs not high risk of disruption yet. 
Fixing broke on oncall pipelines - high risk of disruption
A large majority of pipeline failures are actually false positives caused by badly tuned data quality checks or memory errors. This should be a huge relief to data engineers who are currently 80%+ burnt out! [ https://substack.com/redirect/31bcebe3-b410-4e2a-a2e9-c4e215d07e3a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Technical and Strategic (hard skills that have a long-term focus)
Building data processing frameworks - low risk of disruption
Making improvements to things like Airflow, Spark, etc will still need to be done via humans. AI is good at stitching together things that have already been done before. It‚Äôs not as great at making good improvements on things that already exist. If you don‚Äôt believe me, try having Cursor tackle a large tech debt item in a big code base. It will hallucinate and fail even with the most state-of-the-art models.
Automated data quality - medium risk of disruption
Generating the simple Great Expectations  [ https://substack.com/redirect/3eb27d78-3036-495e-a288-7ea4a355122f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]or SQL Mesh quality check [ https://substack.com/redirect/230e4d9b-3e73-4e4a-a5df-7f7e27097c75?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] queries will be much easier with AI. Having the business context to make these checks really powerful will still be outside the reach of AI for quite some time. 
Writing tests for your pipelines - medium risk of disruption
generating fake input and output data for your pipeline unit test is something AI is really good at doing. Being thorough with testing the edge cases and understanding business relevant tests is still something that engineers need to do
Soft skills and tactical (communication skills focused on day-to-day)
Sprint planning - medium risk of disruption
Sprint planning has a human negotiation element to it that will be harder for AI to replace. The opportunity sizing and organization elements will be greatly streamlined by AI though. 
Writing documentation - medium risk of disruption
Documentation boilerplate will be greatly augmented by AI and the time it takes to maintain good documentation will be reduced. AI will still struggle with business context necessary to completely automate this task though. 
Answering business questions - high risk of disruption
This is only high risk of disruption under the following conditions:
The data engineer models the data correctly and the data documentation is stellar and accessible via AI. 
If these conditions are met, AI will make quick work of 90-95% of business questions
This part for data engineers will go from being a tactical conversation to a strategic knowledge center building task! 
Soft skills and strategic (communication skills focused long-term)
Creating better pipeline generation processes -  low risk of disruption
Getting everybody to agree on what processes are required to create trustable data changes over time. This consensus mechanism within businesses will take a long time for AI to take over. 
Conceptual data modeling -  low risk of disruption
AI is good at brainstorming. Injecting AI with the necessary business context to be great at conceptual data modeling will be difficult. Conceptual data modeling involves a ton of conversations. AI could aid here but at the end of the day, agreeing on what to build is a human activity. 
Creating data best practices -  low risk of disruption
Anything consensus driven is something that will take much longer for AI to solve and even once it does it will take humans a long time to believe that ‚ÄúAI knows better.‚Äù
How tools like Windsurf and Cursor impact data engineering
Development speed has gone up dramatically. When developing pipelines with Windsurf, you mostly need to know the higher level concepts and schemas and Windsurf can fill in the details. 
For example, imagine you had a user table that looks like:
CREATE TABLE users ( user_id BIGINT, country VARCHAR, date DATE)
And you want to track what country each user is and when. If you‚Äôre an experienced data engineer, building a slowly-changing dimension type 2 [ https://substack.com/redirect/6743307b-8b46-4ed6-8d67-6358dfe0bd62?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] should be a bell that rings in your head! You also know that writing that SQL is a giant pain in the ass if you‚Äôve ever done it! 
Instead of writing all that nasty SQL yourself, tell Windsurf this prompt:
Given this schema CREATE TABLE users ( user_id BIGINT, country VARCHAR, date DATE) create me an Airflow DAG using Trino that implements slowly changing dimension type 2 tracking on the country column. Make sure to include partition sensors, quality checks using write-audit-publish pattern and have the DAG be idempotent 
If we examine this prompt, you‚Äôll notice a few important things. 
We start with the inputs. Always give the input schema first in the prompt. 
Then we specify the orchestration technology (i.e. Airflow) and processing technology (i.e. Trino)
Then we specify the design pattern (i.e. slowly changing dimension type 2)
Then we specify any quality concerns and best practices
If you follow this pattern of inputs ‚Üí technologies ‚Üí design pattern ‚Üí best practices, you‚Äôll find that Windsurf does an impeccable job at giving you a DAG that just works! 
So what does this mean for data engineers who used to pride themselves in writing these nasty SQLs themselves? 
LEARN THE CONCEPTS! 
I am sure most of my readers know about schemas and technologies so I‚Äôll be covering the design patterns that you might want to be thinking about. 
Design patterns (in order of usefulness and probability of finding in the wild)
Traditional Dimensional and Fact Tables [ https://substack.com/redirect/74e5f544-6f14-48a2-b22c-4dbf7872e05b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] (i.e. Kimball Data Models)
Useful for generating the master data that is fed into OLAP cubes
OLAP cubes [ https://substack.com/redirect/32fd2e3a-2382-4926-a9c2-67768571bb50?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Useful approach to modeling data for charting
OLTP data modeling [ https://substack.com/redirect/360afdd8-a397-4fcf-9901-87bc30eac70d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] (i.e. third normal form data modeling)
Useful approach to modeling data in transactional systems
Slowly Changing Dimension Type 2
Tracking historical changes of a column on a dimension table
One Big Table data modeling [ https://substack.com/redirect/104406e3-f494-4666-90dc-af58b1828096?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Useful when needing to do large scale analytics of many complex columns without shuffling. Also really powerful for NoSQL use cases!
Machine Learning feature store architecture [ https://substack.com/redirect/4688161f-df43-4d0d-aa1b-f4de4856736b?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Useful when serving downstream machine learning models that need a centralized location 
Kappa Architecture with Apache Flink [ https://substack.com/redirect/3635efab-51a5-4b46-bacb-4f75a37bc62a?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Extremely useful design pattern for anything processed in real-time
Microbatch / Hourly processing [ https://substack.com/redirect/f0bdce9f-9434-4511-a7ad-7522f38eac99?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Useful when deduplicating data in a low-latency way
But what about the best practices?
There‚Äôs really only small set of best practices you need to consider:
Data modeling best practices
Proper naming of tables 
Clear separation of dimension, fact, and aggregation tables
Proper naming of columns 
Don‚Äôt have overly long column names or unclear column names. 
Partitioning
Properly partition your data sets. Almost every data set in your data lake should be partitioned
Personally identifiable information (i.e. PII) management
Minimize the usage of PII and anonymize when possible
Don‚Äôt break any company privacy policies when building the pipeline
Data Lake best practices
Compression
Your data is leveraging run-length encoding compression [ https://substack.com/redirect/f1564a32-b9a0-46e3-8ef5-85219d6caa84?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] the most it can
Your data is stored as Parquet files
Retention
Don‚Äôt hold onto too much or too little data. What determines how much is too much or too little is a balance of analytics capabilities, cloud costs, and legal/privacy constraints.
Data Duplication
Don‚Äôt recreate data sets that already exist. Even the big tech companies get this wrong many many times! 
DAG best practices
Idempotency [ https://substack.com/redirect/20cdc1a0-466c-4525-a761-91a1da1a27b1?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
A task executes properly and the same whether it‚Äôs backfilled or runs in production
This is solved by setting up the right partition sensors and being mindful of if your DAG is a cumulative DAG [ https://substack.com/redirect/a0b452b4-4a43-4d2a-bea8-c9b1c2ef05b3?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]! 
A task executes properly regardless how many times its ran
This is mostly solved by using MERGE or INSERT OVERWRITE instead of INSERT INTO!
Data serving / dashboarding best practices
Latency
Serve your dashboard data from a low-latency store like Druid or Snowflake
Pre-aggregate data before loading into low-latency store
Storage
Don‚Äôt put non-aggregated data into your low-latency stores
I‚Äôm sure I‚Äôm missing some more best practices. Please comment other best practices you would like to include in this list! 
We teach all of these best practices and patterns in the DataExpert.io Academy both as self-paced content as well as cohorts! 
Our next cohort starts May 26th that will cover Databricks, AI, Iceberg, and Delta Live Table! The first 5 people to use code AIREADY at DataExpert.io [ https://substack.com/redirect/c09e175c-52db-4f34-b480-39d5fedf556f?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] can get 30% off either the subscription product or the live boot camp!
